# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hoover-medal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The **1920 Republican National Convention** nominated Ohio Senator Warren G.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Harding for president and Massachusetts Governor Calvin Coolidge for vice president.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The convention was held in Chicago, Illinois, at the Chicago Coliseum from June 8 to June 12, 1920, with 940 delegates.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Under convention rules, a majority plus one, or at least 471 of the 940 delegates, was necessary for a nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Many Republicans sought the presidential nomination, including General Leonard Wood, Illinois Governor Frank Lowden and California Senator Hiram Johnson.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Dark horse Harding, however, was nominated.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Many wanted to nominate Wisconsin Senator Irvine L.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Lenroot for vice president, but Coolidge was nominated instead, because he was known for his response to the Boston Police Strike in 1919.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The convention also adopted a platform opposed to the accession of the United States to the League of Nations.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The plank was carefully drawn up by Henry Cabot Lodge to appease opponents of the League such as Johnson, while still allowing eventual American entry into the League.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] At the start of the convention, the race was wide open.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] General Leonard Wood, Illinois Governor Frank Lowden, and California Senator Hiram Johnson were considered the three most likely nominees.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Harding had been a front-runner, but his star had faded by the time of the convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Many expected a dark horse to be chosen, such as Pennsylvania Governor William Cameron Sproul, Pennsylvania Senator Philander C.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Knox, Kansas Governor Henry Justin Allen, Massachusetts Senator Henry Cabot Lodge, or 1916 nominee Charles Evans Hughes.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Sproul in particular had been gaining momentum at the expense of Lowden, the candidate of the conservative wing of the party.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The issue of joining the League of Nations took center stage at the convention, with some speculating that Johnson would bolt the party if the platform endorsed the League.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The convention adjourned for the night after four ballots produced no clear leader, and many states stuck to favorite-son candidates.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] As the balloting continued the next day, Wood, Lowden, and Johnson remained in the lead, and party leaders worked to find a candidate acceptable to both the progressive and conservative wings of the party.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Conservatives strongly opposed Wood, while Lowden was opposed by the progressive wing of the party.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Harding emerged as a moderately conservative candidate acceptable to the progressive wing of the party, and as the convention remained deadlocked, Harding emerged as a strong compromise candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] After the eighth ballot, the convention recessed.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] During the recess, Harding's managers lobbied Lowden's supporters and others to support Harding.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Harding was also helped by the fact that the Democrats might nominate James M.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Cox of Ohio, and Republicans did not want to give the Democrats a home state advantage in electorally critical Ohio.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Harding jumped into the lead on the ninth ballot, and clinched the nomination on the tenth ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Many thought that Johnson could have stopped the Harding movement by throwing his support behind Knox, who could have displaced Harding as the compromise candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Johnson disliked Harding's policies and disliked Harding personally, and was friends with Knox.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] However, Johnson never released his supporters, and Harding took the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] At the time, Harding's nomination was said to have been secured in negotiations led by party bosses George Harvey and Senator Henry Cabot Lodge in a mysterious "smoke-filled room" at Chicago's Blackstone Hotel." Legend says Harry M.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Daugherty, Harding's political manager was the mastermind.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] After Harding's election he became United States Attorney General.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Daugherty's prediction described essentially what occurred, but historians argue that Daugherty's prediction has been given too much weight in narratives of the convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] The "smoke filled room" was actually a suite rented by National Chairman Will H.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] For six hours the leaders considered numerous alternatives, including Wood, Lowden, and Johnson.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] However, there were objections to all of them.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Headlines in the next morning newspapers suggested intrigue.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Bagby argues, "Various groups actually worked along separate lines to bring about the nomination - without combination and with very little contact." Bagby finds that the key factor in Harding's nomination was his wide popularity among the rank and file of the delegates.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Before Harding was nominated, Johnson, Kansas Governor Henry Justin Allen, Massachusetts Governor Calvin Coolidge, Wisconsin Senator Irvine Lenroot, Kentucky Governor Edwin P.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Morrow, and Harding himself were all seen as possible vice presidential nominees.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Once the presidential nomination was finally settled, Harding and the party bosses asked Johnson to join the ticket as a progressive balance to Harding.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] When Johnson turned down the offer, they approached Lenroot, who accepted.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] However, when Illinois Senator Medill McCormick stood up to nominate Lenroot, several delegates began to shout for Coolidge.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Though initially he had only been nominated after the refusal of Senator Lodge (another Massachusetts man), a groundswell of support built up for Coolidge, who won the nomination over Lenroot; historian Donald R.
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] McCoy called it the first time since the 1880 nomination of James Garfield that "the delegates had taken control of a Republican convention".
[src:hoover-medal/1920-republican-national-convention] Coolidge, who was not at the convention during the vice presidential nomination, agreed to join the ticket.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] The **1928 Republican National Convention** was held at Convention Hall in Kansas City, Missouri, from June 12 to June 15, 1928.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Because President Calvin Coolidge had announced unexpectedly he would not run for re-election in 1928, Commerce Secretary Herbert Hoover became the natural front-runner for the Republican nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Former Illinois Governor Frank Lowden and Kansas Senator Charles Curtis were candidates for the nomination but stood no chance against the popular and accomplished Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Chicago Mayor William Hale Thompson considered himself a candidate, but without the support of Ruth Hanna McCormick, his candidacy was unsuccessful.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Hoover was nominated on the first ballot with 837 votes to 72 for Lowden and 64 for Curtis and the rest scattered.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] McNab delivered Hoover's nomination address.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] In his acceptance speech, Hoover said, "We in America today are nearer to the final triumph over poverty ever before in the history of any land." That and other optimistic remarks about the country's future were used against him in the 1932 election, which he lost to Franklin Roosevelt.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] After Coolidge announced that "I do not choose to run" for a second full term in August 1927, Hoover emerged as the frontrunner.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Illinois Governor Frank Lowden, Vice President Charles Dawes, and Senators James Eli Watson of Indiana, Charles Curtis of Kansas, Guy D.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Goff of West Virginia, and Frank Willis of Ohio were potential challengers to Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Hoover had won respect by many for his work in the Wilson, Harding, and Coolidge administrations, but many party regulars distrusted his loyalty to the party on issues of both policy and patronage.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Some progressive Republicans, such as California Senator Hiram Johnson, also disliked Hoover, but others, such as Senator William E.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Many party leaders pressured Secretary of the Treasury Andrew Mellon to run, but at 73, Mellon felt that he was too old to run in 1928.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Mellon sought to convince former Secretary of State and 1916 Republican nominee Charles Evans Hughes to run, but Hughes refused to campaign for the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Hoover's forces won an early victory by securing adoption of an agricultural plank which endorsed President Coolidge's position on the question and rejected all principles of the McNary–Haugen Farm Relief Bill.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Former Governor Lowden caused a sensation by announcing that since the agricultural plank was unsatisfactory, he withdrew from consideration as presidential nominee.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Party leaders wanted Coolidge to run again, and he would have easily been nominated.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] He sent Secretary to the President Everett Sanders to the convention to tell leaders of state delegations to vote for anyone else.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] With no strong alternative, Hoover appeared to be the likely nominee at the start of the convention, but many in the party still opposed his candidacy.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] A "draft Coolidge" movement emerged, but the movement collapsed after William S.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Vare, political boss of Philadelphia, unexpectedly supported Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Coolidge remained silent, refusing to tell even the delegation from the president's home state of Vermont whether to support the draft.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Curtis sought supporters of Hoover's rivals for his own candidacy.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] However, Hoover won the nomination on the first ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] At the start of the convention, Vice President Charles G.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Dawes was perhaps the most likely running mate for Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Other possibilities included former Kansas Governor Henry Justin Allen, New Jersey Senator Walter Edge, New Hampshire Senator George H.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Moses, Connecticut Representative John Q.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Curtis was also a possibility, but he was not yet ready to concede the presidential nomination to Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] After Hoover won the presidential nomination, Moses, Illinois Senator Charles S.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Deneen, and former Massachusetts Governor Channing Cox were named as the most likely vice-presidential nominees, with a re-nomination for Dawes also a possibility.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Party leaders considered nominating Cox or Dawes, but Cox was vetoed by Utah Senator Reed Smoot, and Dawes was unacceptable to Hoover and Coolidge for supporting McNary-Haugen.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] The convention turned to the farm vote in hopes of placating them for the unfavorably received farm relief plank.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Curtis' name was entered by Senator Borah and his nomination was practically assured since the Lion of Idaho and other westerners had issued an ultimatum that a westerner must hold the vice presidency to placate the farmers.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] The Senate Majority Leader voted for the McNary-Haugen Bill which President Coolidge vetoed, but had refused to vote to override the veto of that measure.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Curtis, possibly with the support of Coolidge, was nominated by the party leaders, and the convention ratified the choice.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Each of the four days of the convention opened with a lengthy invocation by a different clergymen—one Jewish, one Catholic, one Episcopalian, one Methodist.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Together, these four religious groups formed a majority of Americans at the time.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] All of the clergy were based in Missouri, where the convention was held.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Each was listed among the convention officers as an official chaplain.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] On June 12, the opening prayer was given by Bishop S.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Partridge of the Episcopal Diocese of West Missouri.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Speakers on the second through fourth days were Catholic Bishop Thomas F.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Lillis of the Diocese of Kansas City, Rabbi Herman M.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Cohen of Congregation Keneseth Israel-Beth Sholom, Kansas City, and Bishop E.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-republican-national-convention] Waldorf of the Methodist Episcopal Diocese of Kansas City.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 1928.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In a landslide victory, the Republican ticket of Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover and Senator Charles Curtis defeated the Democratic ticket of New York Governor Al Smith and Senator Joseph T.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] After President Calvin Coolidge declined to seek reelection, Hoover emerged as the Republican Party's frontrunner.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] As Hoover's party opponents failed to unite around a candidate, Hoover received a large majority of the vote at the 1928 Republican National Convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The strong state of the economy discouraged some Democrats from running, and Smith was nominated on the first ballot of the 1928 Democratic National Convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover and Smith had been widely known as potential presidential candidates long before the 1928 campaign, and both were generally regarded as outstanding leaders.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Both were newcomers to the presidential race and presented in their person and record an appeal of unknown potency to the electorate.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Both faced serious discontent within their respective parties' membership, and both lacked the wholehearted support of their parties' organization.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Republicans were identified with the booming economy of the 1920s, and Smith, a Roman Catholic, suffered politically from anti-Catholic sentiment particularly in the Solid South, his opposition to Prohibition, and his association with the legacy of corruption by Tammany Hall.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won a third straight Republican landslide and made substantial inroads in the traditionally-Democratic Solid South by winning several states that had not voted for a Republican since the end of Reconstruction.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith carried the five states of the Deep South, his running mate's home state of Arkansas, and the Northeastern states of Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's victory made him the first president born west of the Mississippi River, and he remains the most recent Cabinet secretary to win a presidential election.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Curtis became the first (and thus far the only) Native American vice president, and the first vice president with acknowledged non-European ancestry.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last Republican presidential victory until 1952.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] With President Calvin Coolidge choosing not to seek re-election, the race for the nomination was wide open.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The leading candidates were Secretary of Commerce Herbert Hoover, former Illinois Governor Frank Orren Lowden and Senate Majority Leader Charles Curtis.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] A movement to draft Coolidge failed to gain traction with party insiders or even persuade Coolidge himself.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the few primaries that mattered, Hoover did not perform as well as expected, leaving him with fewer than half the number of pledged delegates that he needed to win the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Lowden in turn only had half the number of delegates that Hoover did, leaving it looking unlikely that the first rounds of voting would produce a majority for any candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Attempts were made to sound out Coolidge and Vice President Charles G.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Dawes as to whether they would be willing to enter the race and break a potential deadlock between Hoover and Lowden, but both Coolidge and Dawes remained aloof.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The matter was unexpectedly resolved when the convention voted to adopt a platform that repudiated the McNary–Haugen Farm Relief Bill, in turn causing Lowden to withdraw his candidacy in protest, and leaving no obvious challenger to Hoover.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The only real competition that remained came from Senator Curtis, whose campaign was left with far too little time to win over the Lowden supporters.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican Convention was held in Kansas City, Missouri from June 12 to 15 and nominated Hoover on the first ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] To attract votes from farmers who were concerned about Hoover's pro-business orientation, the nomination was instead offered to Curtis.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He accepted and was nominated overwhelmingly on the first ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Curtis was the first candidate of Native American ancestry nominated by a major party for national office.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In his acceptance speech eight weeks after the convention ended, Hoover said: "We in America today are nearer to the final triumph over poverty than ever before in the history of this land...
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] We shall soon with the help of God be in sight of the day when poverty will be banished from this land." That sentence would haunt Hoover during the Great Depression.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Owing to the economic prosperity in the country and rapidly fading public memory of the Teapot Dome scandal, the Democratic Party's prospects looked dim.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] New York Governor Al Smith had previously made two attempts to secure the Democratic nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The 1928 Democratic National Convention was held in Houston, Texas, on June 26 to 28, and Smith became the candidate on the first ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The leadership asked the delegates to nominate Senator Joseph Taylor Robinson of Arkansas, in many ways Smith's political polar opposite, to be his running mate, and Robinson was nominated for vice-president.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith was the first Roman Catholic to gain a major party's nomination for president, and his religion became an issue during the campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Many Protestants feared that Smith would take orders from church leaders in the Vatican in making decisions affecting the country.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in the Finnish Socialist Hall in New York City, the eighth Socialist Party Convention met on the thirteenth of April.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] James Maurer, a former State Representative, President of the Pennsylvania Federation of Labor and then Councilman for the city of Reading, was widely considered the frontrunner in the months before the convention met.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] For his boomers however, Maurer stood that his duties as councilman precluded the possibility of any national tour that would be required of his nomination for the presidency, and this declination was made definitive on the tenth of April.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Norman Thomas, a Presbyterian minister who had been one of Maurer's boomers and had himself made it known that he was not a candidate for the Socialist nomination rather swiftly became the new frontrunner, and plans were made for a draft effort.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas and Maurer were nominated unanimously for president and vice president respectively, with both men accepting their nominations.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The only trouble arose on the question of Prohibition, where there remained a split in the party between those who supported the Eighteenth Amendment and those, like Convention Chair Victor Berger, who preferred that it be handled on a state-by-state basis.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the end it was agreed that the party remain silent on the issue of Prohibition.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in the Mecca Temple in New York City, the second Workers Party Convention met on the twenty-fifth of May.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Jay Lovestone served as the convention's keynote speaker, denouncing the Democratic, Republican and Socialist Parties and claiming that the Communists would turn the next "imperialist war" into a civil war.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Party Chair William Foster was named as the party's candidate for the presidency while Benjamin Gitlow, a former opponent of Foster's within the party, was named as its candidate for vice president.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Scott Nearing was also considered a possible contender for either position on ticket.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in New York City, the tenth Socialist Labor Party Convention met on the twelfth of May.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] With their standard-bearer having passed, the executive committee of the party tendered the presidential nomination to Reynolds, with the place of vice presidential nominee being filled by Jeremiah Crowley of New York.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Speaking of the "decay of the Capitalistic System", Reynolds campaigned on the idea of Industrial democracy.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held at the La Salle Hotel in Chicago, the fifteenth Prohibition Party Convention met on the tenth of July.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Leigh Colvin and other Prohibitionists had found both the Republican and Democratic planks regarding Prohibition as unsatisfactory, and there was open discussion of nominating a ticket despite the continued reversals the party had suffered since 1920.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Those opposed to Hoover rallied on the second ballot however behind frontrunner William Varnery, an insurance salesman and party regular from New York.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] James Edgerton, a Virginian native who had headed the Jefferson-Lincoln League in the failed effort to fuse the Prohibition and Farmer-Labor Parties, was nominated for the vice presidency.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, there remained a concerted effort to withdraw the ticket from the race, resulting in a meeting by the Party National Executive Committee on whether Varney should drop out.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Varney himself was opposed to this plan, and in a narrow vote, four to three, the effort to effectively endorse Hoover for the presidency failed.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Held in Chicago, the third Farmer-Labor Party Convention met on the tenth of July.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] To run alongside Norris the party had named William J.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Vereen of Georgia, a cotton textile manufacturer, but refused to consider his nomination under any circumstances once the press had brought it to his attention.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Alexander of North Carolina was then nominated in Reed's stead, but on September 18 Alexander requested that his name be withdrawn from the ticket and he later endorsed Al Smith for the presidency.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] At some point after LeRoy Tillman, a nephew of the late Senator Benjamin Tillman of South Carolina, was nominated in Alexander's stead.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Catholicism was a significant burden for Smith's campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Protestant ministers warned that he would take orders from the Pope, whom many Americans sincerely believed would move to the United States to rule the country from a fortress in Washington, DC.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] An example was a statement issued in September 1928 by the National Lutheran Editors' and Managers' Association that opposed Smith's election.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Groups circulated a million copies of a counterfeit oath, claiming that fourth-degree Knights of Columbus members swore to exterminate Freemasons and Protestants and to commit violence against anyone if the church ordered.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith's opposition to Prohibition, a key reform promoted by Protestants, also lost him votes, as did his association with Tammany Hall.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Because many anti-Catholics used the issues to cover for their religious prejudices, Smith's campaign had difficulty denouncing anti-Catholicism as bigotry without offending others who favored Prohibition or disliked Tammany corruption.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Contemporary Prohibition activists said that their main problem with the Democratic candidate was his faith and not any political view.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Bob Jones Sr., a prominent Protestant pastor in South Carolina, said: "I'll tell you, brother, that the big issue we've got to face ain't the liquor question.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] I'd rather see a saloon on every corner of the South than see the foreigners elect Al Smith president".
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] A Methodist newspaper in Georgia called Catholicism "a degenerate type of Christianity," while Southern Baptist churches ordered their followers to vote against Smith, claiming that he would close down Protestant churches, end freedom of worship and prohibit reading the Bible.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hillman Fountain, a Protestant writer, insisted that Catholics should be barred from holding any office.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Farris states that "More disturbing than the ridiculous and the dangerous was the respectable anti-Catholicism", as contemporary newspapers and Protestant churches tried to mask their anti-Catholicism as genuine concern.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Protestant activists insisted that Catholicism represented an alien culture and medieval mentality, claiming that Catholicism was incompatible with American democracy and institutions.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Catholics were portrayed as reactionary despite being more left-wing than mainstream American Protestant congregations at the time.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Those issues made Smith lose several states of the Solid South that had been carried by Democrats since Reconstruction.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This overcame opposition to Smith's campaign in areas with large nonvoting black populations.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Bilbo claimed that Hoover had met with a black member of the Republican National Committee and danced with her.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's campaign quickly denied the "untruthful and ignoble assertion".
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The total vote exceeded that of 1924 by nearly eight million, which was nearly twice the vote cast in 1916 and nearly three times that of 1896.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Every section in the Union increased its vote although the Mountain, East South Central and West South Central States did so least of all.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The greatest increases were in the heavily populated (Northeastern) Mid-Atlantic and East North Central States, where more than 4,250,000 more votes were cast, more than half of the nationwide increase.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] There was an increase of over a million each in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Much of the increase could be attributed to women voting in ever increasing numbers since gaining the national vote in 1920.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won 200 counties in the Southern United States while Smith won 122 traditionally Republican counties in the Northern United States, with 77 of those counties being majority Catholic.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Harding had won in all twelve cities with populations above 500,000 in the 1920 election, but Smith won in Cleveland, Milwaukee, New York City, San Francisco, and St.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Louis, and lost in Baltimore and Pittsburgh by less than 10,000 votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won in the traditionally Democratic Birmingham, Dallas, and Houston.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith was the first Democratic nominee in the 20th century to win a majority of the twelve largest cities in the country.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The net vote totals in the twelve largest cities shifted from Republican to Democratic with Harding having won by 1,540,000 in 1920, Coolidge by 1,308,000 in 1924, while Smith won by 210,000.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Samuel Lubell wrote in *The Future of American Politics* that Franklin D.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's victory in the 1932 election was preceded by Smith's increased vote totals in urban areas.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith's results in the cities in the election improved upon John W.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In the boroughs of New York City the vote percentages rose from 33.6% to 67.7% in The Bronx, 39.6% to 60.8% in Manhattan, 31.9% to 59.5% in Brooklyn, 31% to 53.4% in Queens, and 42% to 53.4% in Staten Island.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He improved in all of those cities from James M.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover won the election by a wide margin on pledges to continue the economic boom of the Coolidge years.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] He received more votes than any previous candidate of the Republican Party in every state except five: Rhode Island, Iowa, North Dakota, South Carolina, and Tennessee.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Hoover vote was greater than the Coolidge vote in 2,932 counties; it was less in 143 of the comparable counties.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The 21,400,000 votes cast for Hoover also touched the high-water mark for all votes for a presidential candidate until then and were an increase of more than 5,500,000 over the Coolidge vote four years earlier.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican ticket made substantial inroads in the South: the heaviest Democratic losses were in the three Southern sections (South Atlantic, East South Central, West South Central).
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, eight counties recorded more votes cast for "anti-Smith" electors than either major-party candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 7.48% of Hoover's votes, with him taking 47.41% of the vote in that region.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] This was the best showing for a Republican in that region at that point in time.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral votes of North Carolina and Virginia had not been awarded to a Republican since 1872, and Florida had not been carried by a Republican since the heavily disputed election of 1876.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Texas was carried by a Republican for the first time in its history, which left Georgia as the only remaining state never carried by a Republican presidential candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia would not be won by a Republican until 1964, when Barry Goldwater carried the state.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith also carried staunchly Democratic Alabama by barely 7,000 votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In all, Smith carried only six of the eleven states of the former Confederacy, the fewest carried by a Democratic candidate since the end of Reconstruction.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith polled more votes than had any previous Democratic candidate in 30 of the 48 states, all but Alabama, Colorado, Delaware, Idaho, Kansas, Kentucky, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Virginia, and Washington.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In only four of them (Tennessee, Oklahoma, Texas, and New Mexico) did Smith receive fewer votes than Davis had in 1924.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Allan Lichtman notes that since the sole defining issue of the election was anti-Catholicism, it radically realigned states' voting patterns.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover carried Texas, Florida, North Carolina, and Virginia — none of which had backed a post-Reconstruction Republican, while Smith carried historically-Republican Massachusetts and Rhode Island despite the national Republican landslide.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Smith became the first Democrat to ever win a majority of the vote in Massachusetts, and the first since 1852 to win a majority in Rhode Island.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Lichtman further proves this by pointing out that Smith and Hoover had very similar political views save for religion and Prohibition, and yet the 1928 election had a turnout of 57%, despite previous 1920s American elections having their turnouts below 50%.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith received nearly as many votes as Coolidge had in 1924, and his vote exceeded Davis's by more than 6,500,000.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic vote was greater than in 1924 in 2080 counties and fell in 997 counties.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] In only one section did the Democratic vote drop below 38%, the Pacific, which was the only one in which the Republican vote exceeded 60%.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democrats made gains in five sections; of those counties, fourteen had never been Democratic and seven had been Democratic only once.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The size and the nature of the distribution of the Democratic vote illustrated Smith's strengths and weaknesses as a candidate.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Despite evidence of an increased Democratic vote, Smith's overwhelming defeat in the electoral college and the retention of so few Democratic counties reflected Hoover's greater appeal.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith won the electoral votes of only the Deep South of the Democratic Solid South, Robinson's home state of Arkansas, and the New England states of Massachusetts and Rhode Island, both of which had a large proportion of Catholic voters.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] His 87 electoral votes were the fewest that a Democratic candidate had won since the 80 votes earned by Horatio Seymour in 1868.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover even carried Smith's home state of New York by a narrow margin.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Smith carried 914 counties, the fewest in the Fourth Party System.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican total leaped to 2,174 counties, a larger number than even the 1920 landslide.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Third-party support sank almost to the vanishing point, as the election of 1928 proved to be a two-party contest to a greater extent than any other in the Fourth Party System.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] Until the major split before the 1948 election in the Democratic Party between Southern Democrats and the more liberal Northern faction, no further significant third-party candidacies as seen in 1912 and 1924 were to occur.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] All "other" votes totaled only 1.08 percent of the national popular vote.
[src:hoover-medal/1928-united-states-presidential-election] The Socialist vote sank to 267,478, and in seven states, there were no Socialist votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1929-state-of-the-union-address] The **1929 State of the Union Address** was sent as a written message by Herbert Hoover, the 31st United States President on Tuesday, December 3, 1929, to both houses of the 71st United States Congress.
[src:hoover-medal/1929-state-of-the-union-address] This was Hoover's first State of the Union message, and the 1929 stock market crash had just begun.
[src:hoover-medal/1929-state-of-the-union-address] From a foreign relations standpoint, the President noted that the Kellogg-Briand pact was a great advancement in foreign diplomacy and abatement of wars.
[src:hoover-medal/1929-state-of-the-union-address] The President also mentioned the advancement of the Hoover Dam project.
[src:hoover-medal/1930-state-of-the-union-address] The **1930 State of the Union Address** was delivered by President Herbert Hoover on December 2, 1930, in the second year of his presidency and during the early stages of the Great Depression.
[src:hoover-medal/1930-state-of-the-union-address] Hoover focused on the government's response to the economic crisis, which included promoting voluntary cooperation between businesses, labor, and government to avoid mass unemployment and wage cuts.
[src:hoover-medal/1930-state-of-the-union-address] He reported that many businesses had maintained wages, which helped preserve the country’s buying power.
[src:hoover-medal/1930-state-of-the-union-address] Internationally, Hoover addressed the global nature of the economic depression, attributing part of the crisis to overproduction of key commodities, political instability, and economic struggles in other nations.
[src:hoover-medal/1930-state-of-the-union-address] He expressed optimism that the U.S., with its strong resources and self-sustaining economy, would "lead the march of prosperity" once the global economy recovered.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] The **1932 Republican National Convention** was held at Chicago Stadium in Chicago, Illinois, from June 14 to June 16, 1932.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] It nominated President Herbert Hoover and Vice President Charles Curtis for reelection.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Hoover was virtually unopposed for the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Despite the economic crisis facing the country, the convention praised Hoover and pledged itself to maintain a balanced budget.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Republicans gloomily gathered in Chicago for the 20th Republican National Convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Los Angeles attorney Joseph Scott delivered President Hoover's nominating address, praising him as the man who taught the nation to resist the temptations of governmental paternalism.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Hoover was re-nominated on the first ballot without significant opposition.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] To have repudiated the incumbent would have destroyed what little chance of victory the party had amid the worst economic depression in U.S. history.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] France of Maryland attempted to engineer a "draft Coolidge" movement, but the former president expressed no interest in the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Vice President Curtis experienced more difficulties than President Hoover in securing his party's re-nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] It took the fervid appeals of Hoover's cabinet members to keep the Illinois delegation from nominating former Vice President Charles Dawes for his old office.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Curtis nonetheless still had to fight for his re-nomination despite the disorganization of his opposition by the advance refusal of Dawes to accept the nomination for second place.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] Ambassador Hanford MacNider and RCA Chairman James Harbord, both military professionals, were the primary beneficiaries of the opposition to Curtis.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] The initial roll call revealed Curtis to be 18 votes shy of securing re-nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] At this point, Pennsylvania switched its 75 votes from favorite son Edward Martin to Curtis.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-republican-national-convention] After Curtis had secured the vice presidential nomination, the delegates moved to make his re-nomination unanimous.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1932.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Against the backdrop of the Great Depression, the Republican ticket of President Herbert Hoover and Vice President Charles Curtis were defeated, in a landslide, by the Democratic ticket of Franklin D.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, the governor of New York, and John Nance Garner, the Speaker of the House.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This realigning election marked the effective end of the Fourth Party System, which had been dominated by Republicans, and the beginning of an era of Democratic dominance under the New Deal coalition.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Despite disastrous economic conditions due to the Great Depression, Hoover faced little opposition at the 1932 Republican National Convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt was widely considered the front-runner at the start of the 1932 Democratic National Convention, but was not able to clinch the nomination until the fourth ballot of the convention.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic convention chose a leading Southern Democrat, Speaker of the House John Nance Garner of Texas, as the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt united the party, campaigning on the failures of the Hoover administration.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] He promised recovery with a "New Deal" for the American people.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt won by a landslide in both the electoral college and popular vote, carrying every state outside of the Northeast and receiving the highest percentage of the popular vote of any Democratic nominee up to that time.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover had won over 58% of the popular vote in the 1928 presidential election, but his share of the popular vote declined to 39.6% in 1932.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Socialist Party nominee Norman Thomas won 2.2% of the popular vote.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Subsequent Democratic landslides in the 1934 midterm elections and the 1936 presidential election confirmed the commencement of the Fifth Party System, which was dominated by Roosevelt's New Deal Coalition.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's election ended the era of Republican dominance in presidential politics that had lasted since the beginning of the Civil War and the election of 1860.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt was the first Democrat to be elected president since 1916, the first to win an outright majority of the popular vote since 1876, and the first to win a majority of both the electoral and popular vote since 1852.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover was the only incumbent president to lose an election between 1912 and 1976, and the only elected incumbent to do so between 1912 and 1980.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Republican nominee Herbert Hoover had won in the 1928 presidential election against Democratic nominee Al Smith.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Smith had lost the support of the Solid South during the campaign likely due to anti-Catholic sentiment.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover had won in a landslide with him winning forty of the forty-eight states giving him 444 electoral votes against Smith's 87.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and the Great Depression weakened the power of the Republicans.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] In the 1930 elections, the Democrats gained control of the United States House of Representatives, reduced the Republican majority in the United States Senate to one, and won a majority of the governorships.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The net vote totals in the twelve largest cities shifted from Republican to Democratic with Harding having won 1,540,000 in 1920, Coolidge by 1,308,000 in 1924, while Smith won by 210,000.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Smith, who announced his candidacy on February 6, 1932, was a leading candidate as he had remained active in the party and retained his support from the 1928 campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Joseph Taylor Robinson, who had been Smith's vice-presidential running mate, announced that he would not be a candidate on March 31, 1932, and gave his support to Franklin D.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Straus conducted a poll of the delegates to the 1928 Democratic National Convention which showed that the majority supported Roosevelt and additional polling showed Roosevelt winning in the primary and general election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Representative Edgar Howard stated that "Nine out of ten men in nine out of ten states are for Roosevelt, and he will be the Democratic choice." Roosevelt announced his campaign on January 23, 1932.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Murray ran in multiple primaries and won one delegate in the North Dakota primary, but failed to win in the Florida, Nebraska, Oregon, and West Virginia primaries.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] He won in the Ohio primary as he was the only candidate on the ballot, but the delegates were instructed by the convention and not the primary.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Oklahoma convention selected to give him control of its twenty-two member delegation.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Baker declined to run in the primaries and instead planned on serving as a compromise candidate if neither Smith nor Roosevelt could win the nomination at the convention balloting.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton Lewis won the presidential primary in Illinois on April 12, 1932, and the state's fifty-eight member delegation was instructed to vote for him, but he withdrew before the convention on June 25.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The majority of the Illinois delegation supported Melvin Alvah Traylor for the first three ballots before giving their support to Roosevelt on the fourth ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Tom Pendergast, a political boss in Missouri, had the state's delegation instructed to vote for James A.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Reed, who had run for the nomination in the 1928 election, and the delegation supported Reed for the first three ballots before switching to Roosevelt.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Byrd and George White were favorite son candidates from their states.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Harry Moore was a favorite son candidate supported by Lewis, but the delegation of his home state New Jersey voted for Smith.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Both Smith and Roosevelt were against Prohibition, but Smith supported making it a main issue during the campaign while Roosevelt did not.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Raskob, who had become the chair of the Democratic National Committee with Smith's support, attempted to have the committee make a statement against prohibition in March 1931, and Smith gave a speech in support of it.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] James Farley, the chair of the New York State Democratic Committee and later Roosevelt's presidential campaign manager, had the New York committee pass a resolution opposing declarations before the national convention was held.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Other state parties supported this resolution causing the vote to not happen.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Raskob proposed the declaration again on January 9, 1932, but had the committee not take action on it.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Tammany Hall and Roosevelt had a truce during his governorship, but the organization came to openly oppose him for his role in Mayor Jimmy Walker's resignation.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Tammany Hall supported Smith for the nomination at the convention causing Roosevelt to refuse to support their mayoral candidate in the 1933 election and to support Fiorello La Guardia in the 1937 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Tammany Hall's power was also reduced by the adoption of proportional representation for the New York City Council.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt also gave support to the American Labor Party in order for Democratic voters to support the New Deal without giving support to Tammany Hall candidates.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] O'Connor, who represented one of the districts with the strongest Tammany influence and was the chair of the House Rules Committee, lost renomination in the Democratic primary and in the general election with the Republican nomination in the 1938 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Smith's strategy against Roosevelt was to use favorite son candidates to control the delegations of their states in places that would have otherwise gone for Roosevelt.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The majority of Smith's support came from the northeast while Roosevelt's support came from the south and west.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Howard McGrath, Moore, Raskob, and Jouett Shouse were among Smith's campaign leaders.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt attempted to have some of the favorite son candidates withdraw using Homer Stille Cummings as a mediator, but he was unsuccessful.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Seventeen states used primaries to select their delegates to the national conventions while the rest used a convention system.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt controlled the delegations from thirty states and additional delegations from Arkansas, Indiana, Kansas, and South Carolina had supporters of Roosevelt, but were uninstructed.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt was endorsed at the state convention in Mississippi, but the delegates were left uninstructed.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt also claimed that he had the support of the twenty-eight delegates from all of the territories.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Smith controlled the delegates from four states.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining delegations were either uninstructed or under the control of favorite sons.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt failed to gain control of two-thirds of the delegates which was required for him to gain the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was held in Chicago between June 27 and July 2.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The first vote was taken at 4:28 on the morning of July 2, after ten hours of speeches that had begun at 5:00 on the previous afternoon.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Roosevelt delegations from Louisiana and Minnesota were seated giving Roosevelt an additional thirty-two votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Walsh, an ally of Roosevelt, was elected to chair the convention against Shouse by a vote of 626 to 528.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt received the most votes on the first three ballots, but he still did not have a two-thirds majority.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] John Nance Garner, who had the support of William Randolph Hearst, won in the California primary due to the support of the Texas State Society of California which had 100,000 members.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Garner had the support of ninety delegates at the convention and Hearst created a compromise with Roosevelt.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, who needed the support of the Californian and Texan delegations to gain a two-thirds majority, would receive the support of Garner's delegates in exchange for Garner being given the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] With this agreement, Garner's supporters in California and Texas were released by Sam Rayburn, Garner's campaign manager, and voted for Roosevelt on the fourth ballot, giving him the presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Members of the Texas delegation who opposed Roosevelt were led by Amon G.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Carter, but the Roosevelt supporters led by Thomas Whitfield Davidson won by a vote of 54 to 51.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York, and Rhode Island were the only states whose delegations did not support Roosevelt on the final ballot.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Garner won the vice-presidential nomination on the first ballot against Matthew A.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Tinley and his nomination was made unanimous.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] In November 1931, Senator Hiram Johnson called for Hoover to retire as it would increase the chances of the Republicans winning in the 1932 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's opponents in the Republican Party supported giving either former President Calvin Coolidge or Senator Dwight Morrow the party's presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Senate from New Jersey in 1930, but died on October 5, 1931.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] On July 31, 1931, an article by James F.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Coupal, Coolidge's former White House physician, was published by the *St.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Coolidge did not run for the nomination and an article written by him was published by *The Saturday Evening Post* on October 3, 1932, in which he gave his support to Hoover and was critical of those who had wanted him to run.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Dawes was suggested as a candidate following Morrow's death and the unsuccessful attempt to draft Coolidge, but his selection as president of the Reconstruction Finance Corporation took him out of consideration.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Progressive Republicans considered forming a third party, but William Borah, Johnson, George W.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Norris, and Gifford Pinchot declined to lead such a movement.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] An attempt to have progressive leaders in multiple states run against Hoover failed and Borah stated that Hoover could not be defeated.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover formally started his campaign by having Robert H.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Lucas, executive director of the Republican National Committee, send out letters to precinct leaders in January 1931.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Walter Folger Brown and Treasury Secretary Ogden L.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Theodore Joslin started a publicity campaign to improve Hoover's image.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] France, a member of the conservative faction, ran against Hoover in the primary, but only won in states where he was unopposed.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] These states also had no delegates bounded to their primaries leading to them sending pro-Hoover delegations.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] At the national convention Lawritz Bernhard Sandblast, a delegate from Oregon, nominated France, but France attempted to address the convention to withdraw his candidacy and instead nominate Coolidge.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover had him removed citing that he could not address the convention as he was not a delegate.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover, who was nominated by Joseph Scott, won renomination on the first ballot while France only received four delegates.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Dawes was proposed as a replacement for Vice President Charles Curtis, who faced opposition due to his age and prohibitionist stances, and delegations from over twenty states opposed the renomination of Curtis.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] However, Dawes declined to seek the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Fuller, James Harbord, Hanford MacNider, J.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Leonard Replogle, and Bertrand Snell were nominated for the vice-presidential balloting.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Curtis initially fell 19.25 votes short of winning on the first ballot, but the Pennsylvania delegation changed its support to Curtis causing him to win.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Norman Thomas, who had been the Socialist Party of America's presidential nominee in the 1928 election and ran for a seat in the U.S.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives in the 1930 election, and James H.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Maurer, who was the party's vice-presidential nominee in the 1928 election, were given the Socialist Party presidential and vice-presidential nominations at the national convention held May 21–24 in Milwaukee.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas and his faction unsuccessfully tried to have Morris Hillquit replaced as chair of the party by Daniel Hoan.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] *The Literary Digest'*s polling predicted that Thomas would receive over two million votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Foster, who had been the Communist Party USA's presidential nominee in the 1928 election, was given the presidential nomination at the national convention held from May 28–29 in Chicago, and James W.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Ford was given the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Coxey Sr., former mayor of Massillon, Ohio, were given the presidential and vice-presidential nominations of the Farmer–Labor Party at its convention on April 28 in Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Townley had also been proposed as candidates for the nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] However, Webb was removed from the ticket with the party stating that he was "a tool of the Hoover administration," and Coxey was given the presidential nomination.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Minnesota Farmer–Labor Party did not support the national party's ticket.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] After the Farmer-Labor presidential nomination was taken from him, Webb formed the Liberty Party with him as its presidential nominee while the larger Liberty Party gave its nomination to William Hope Harvey.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Samuel Harden Church, who had formed the Liberal Party in Pennsylvania which received 366,572 votes on its ballot line in the 1930 gubernatorial election, unsuccessfully tried to form a national anti-prohibitionist Liberal Party.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Nicholas Murray Butler proposed the creation of a new party on May 19, 1932, which would be composed of the moderate wings of both existing Democratic and Republican parties.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] After making an airplane trip to the Democratic convention, Roosevelt accepted the nomination in person.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Large crowds greeted Roosevelt as he traveled around the nation; his campaign song "Happy Days Are Here Again" became one of the most popular in American political history – and, indeed, the unofficial anthem of the Democratic Party.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders in the eastern United States supported having Roosevelt conduct a front porch campaign, but Roosevelt and the leaders in the western United States instead supported an active campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt gave twenty-seven major speeches during the campaign while Hoover initially planned on giving three major speeches during the campaign, but it was later increased to ten and Hoover traveled over 10,000 miles.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Fess, who had become chair of the Republican National Committee with Hoover's support, resigned from his position and was replaced by Everett Sanders also with Hoover's support.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Raskob, who became the chair of the Democratic National Convention with Smith's support, was replaced by Farley.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Campaign expenditures for both parties fell from the 1928 election to the 1932 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The combined expenditures of both national committees would be $5,146,027 which was less than $0.13 per voter.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This was the lowest amount spent per voter since the 1912 election with most elections costing around $0.19–0.20 per voter and the 1924 presidential election costing $0.15 per voter.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties spent large amounts on radio campaigns with 17–18% of Democratic and over 20% of the Republican national committees spending being towards radio.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] During the 1928 election the Republicans paid $420,000 to radio companies and increased their spending to $437,000 during the 1932 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats reduced their spending with their amount falling from $550,000 during the 1928 election to $343,415 during the 1932 election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign NBC and CBS aired 203 programs of paid time that took up 116 hours and 15 minutes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] One hundred thirty-six of those programs were for the Republicans, seventy-one for the Democrats, and three for the Socialists.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans had seventy hours and thirty-two minutes, the Democrats had forty-nine hours and thirty-two minutes, and the Socialists had forty-five minutes of air time.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt made gains with voters compared to Smith's 1928 campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The southerners who had supported Hoover in the 1928 campaign returned to the Democratic Party and progressive Republicans under the leadership of Bronson M.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Wallace left the Republicans to support Roosevelt.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Farley predicted that Roosevelt would win in forty-four states and later congratulated Sanders on his imagination and courage when Sanders predicted that Hoover would win 338 electoral votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] After their divisive convention, Democrats united around Roosevelt, who was able to draw more universal support than Al Smith had in 1928.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's Protestant background prevented the anti-Catholic attacks Smith faced in 1928, and the Depression seemed to be of much greater concern among the American public than previous cultural battles.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Prohibition was increasingly unpopular, and wets offered the argument that states and localities needed the tax money.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover proposed a new constitutional amendment that was vague on particulars and satisfied neither side.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's platform promised repeal of the 18th Amendment.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast, Hoover was not supported by many of the more prominent Republicans and violently opposed by others, in particular by a number of senators who had fought him throughout his administration and whose national reputation made their opposition of considerable importance.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Many prominent Republicans even went so far as to espouse the cause of the Democratic candidate openly.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Making matters worse for Hoover was that many Americans blamed him for the Great Depression.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The outrage caused by the deaths of veterans in the Bonus Army incident in the summer of 1932, combined with the catastrophic economic effects of Hoover's domestic policies, reduced his chances of a second term from slim to none.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] His attempts to campaign in public were a disaster, as he often had objects thrown at him or his vehicle as he rode through city streets.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover's unpopularity resulted in Roosevelt's adoption of a cautious campaign strategy, focused on minimizing gaffes and keeping public attention directed towards his opponent.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] As governor of New York, Roosevelt had garnered a reputation for promoting government help for the impoverished, providing a welcome contrast for many who saw Hoover as a do-nothing president.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt emphasized working collectively through an expanded federal government to confront the economic crisis, a contrast to Hoover's emphasis on individualism.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign, Roosevelt ran on many of the programs that would later become part of the New Deal during his presidency.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt employed the radio to great effect during the campaign.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] He was able to outline his platform while also improving the perception of his personality.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt took great pains to hide the effects of the disease from voters, instituting a "gentleman's agreement" with the press that he was not to be photographed in ways that would highlight his disability.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt defeated Hoover in the election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover became the seventh president to lose reelection after John Adams, John Quincy Adams, Martin Van Buren, Grover Cleveland, Benjamin Harrison, and William Howard Taft.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Another president would not lose an election to another term until Gerald Ford was defeated by Jimmy Carter in the 1976 presidential election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1916 (16 years earlier) in which the Democratic candidate won.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt was the last sitting governor to be elected president until Bill Clinton in 1992.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election where a Socialist Party presidential candidate received over 500,000 votes as of 2024.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, the Democratic candidate, received 22,817,883 votes (57.41%), the largest vote ever cast for a candidate for the presidency up until that time, and over 1,425,000 more than that cast for Hoover four years earlier.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt improved on Smith's net vote total performance in the twelve largest cities.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Smith had won those areas by 210,000 votes in the 1928 election while Roosevelt won by 1,791,000 votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's worst performance in the country was in the eastern United States where all six of the states that voted for Hoover came from.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover only won in forty-five counties west of the Mississippi.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The 0.09% difference between the tipping point state (Iowa) and the national popular vote is tied as the smallest in history (along with 1892).
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This was a political realignment election: not only did Roosevelt win a sweeping victory over Hoover, but Democrats significantly extended their control over the U.S.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] House, gaining 101 seats, and also gained 12 seats in the U.S.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Twelve years of Republican leadership came to an end, and 20 consecutive years of Democratic control of the White House began.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Until 1932, the Republicans had controlled the presidency for 52 of the previous 72 years, dating back to Abraham Lincoln being elected president in 1860.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] After 1932, Democrats would control the presidency for 32 of the next 48 years.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt led the poll in 2,722 counties, the greatest number ever carried by a candidate up until that time.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, 282 had never before been Democratic.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Half of the total vote of the nation was cast in just eight states (New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, and Wisconsin); in these states, Hoover polled 8,592,163 votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] In one section (West South Central), the Republican percentage sank to 16.21%, but in no other section did the party poll less than 30% of the vote cast.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] However, the relative appeal of the two candidates in 1932 and the decline of the appeal of Hoover as compared with 1928 are shown in the fact that the Republican vote increased in 1932 in only 87 counties, while the Democratic vote increased in 3,003 counties.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover also failed to flip any counties; the next time this would happen was in 2024, over 90 years later.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Hoover is also the most recent Republican candidate not to flip any counties.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The Roosevelt ticket swept every region of the country except the Northeast, and carried many reliable Republican states that had not been carried by the Democrats since their electoral landslide of 1912, when the Republican vote was split in two.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt's victory with 472 electoral votes stood until the 1964 victory of Lyndon B.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Johnson, who won 486 electoral votes in 1964, as the most ever won by a first-time contestant in a presidential election.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt also bettered the national record of 444 electoral votes set by Hoover only four years earlier, but would shatter his own record when he was re-elected in 1936 with 523 votes.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Connecticut, Delaware, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania voted Republican until 1948.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] The eleven states of the former Confederacy provided 4.45% of Hoover's votes, with him taking 18.55% of the vote in that region.
[src:hoover-medal/1932-united-states-presidential-election] His share of the vote in the South sharply declined from the 47.41% he received in 1928.
[src:hoover-medal/hoover-medal] The **Hoover Medal** is an American engineering prize.
[src:hoover-medal/hoover-medal] It has been given since 1930 for "outstanding extra-career services by engineers to humanity".
[src:hoover-medal/hoover-medal] It is named for Herbert Hoover, the first recipient, who was an engineer by profession.
